### Anti-log Rule

A log says "this happened, then that happened." A holistic RCA says "this
system had these boundaries; this invariant failed by this mechanism; this
evidence eliminated these alternatives; this repair closes these state planes;
this replay proves it." Timelines are evidence surfaces, not the document
spine. If the document can be reordered into timestamp order without losing its
main structure, it is log-shaped and fails this skill.

## Skill Selection Gate

Use this skill to produce an RCA **output package** whose primary document lets
a reader with **zero context** become a master of the incident — able to
replicate the troubleshooting end-to-end, name every component and its purpose,
walk the evidence chain, defend the conclusions under adversarial questioning,
and recognize the same pattern next time.

Minimum package shape for non-trivial RCAs is `output/` (the four docs `rca.md`, `how-to-fix.md`, `how-to-recreate-this-rca.md`, `sre-toil-removal-proposal.md`) + `antecedents/` + `proofs/{scripts,outputs}/` + optional `auxiliary/`. **When scaffolding the package or deciding which sibling documents are mandatory, read `assets/templates/rca-skeleton.md.tmpl` for the exact directory tree and the per-document contract.** For a tiny single-component RCA, `antecedents/`/`proofs/` may be minimal but the RCA must name why. A complex RCA that cites commands but ships no proof surface is unfinished. If the template is unavailable, the four `output/` docs remain mandatory for a standard package and the package halts per the `SKELETON-TEMPLATE-MISSING` rule in Operational surfaces.

| Situation | Use This Skill? | Why |
|---|---|---|
| You have an existing diagnosis / verified-diagnosis / troubleshooting log and need a holistic RCA | YES | Core job |
| You have raw incident notes (slack, kubectl, az output snippets) and need a structured story-like RCA | YES | Core job — input gating + level decomposition handle the gap |
| The reader will use the doc to teach future on-call shifts (transferable mastery) | YES | Built into the explicit endgame |
| You want every command in the doc paired with the question it answers and a falsifier | YES | Core discipline (see "Probe-rationale pairing" below) |
| You need cross-deliverable coherence with sibling docs (PR description, Slack reply, explanation) | YES | Adversarial dispatch covers this |
| Forward-looking failure analysis ("what could go wrong with this design") | NO | Use `pre-mortem` |
| Blameless postmortem for the retro meeting (audience = stakeholders, voice = neutral, scope = process+systems) | NO | Different deliverable; the holistic RCA is engineer-to-engineer mastery transfer, not stakeholder communication |
| PR description, runbook, runtime triage, or live alert response | NO | Use the dedicated skills |
| Just summarize a diagnosis without re-verifying inherited claims | NO | This skill always runs the freshness audit |

## What this skill teaches the agent

A naive "write an RCA" rearranges the inherited diagnosis: same claims, prettier headings, no challenge, commands without rationale, decorative diagrams. This skill replaces that with sixteen mental-model-first disciplines, each implemented by an X-rule, a heuristic, and a reference. **When orienting to the full discipline set or onboarding a new contributor, read `references/discipline-index.md` for the enumerated 16 with their reference cross-links.** If that file is unavailable, the X-rules (Cross-level rules) and the Heuristics section below still carry every discipline's enforceable form — the index is a map, not a gate. The mental-model map is *what* this skill teaches; the references are *how*.

## Cross-level rules

Fifteen rules apply across all levels. The validator machine-checks X2
vocabulary continuity, parts of X1 via G6/G11, final-package enforcement for
X5/X6 via G13/G14/G15/G16, Knowledge Contract structure via G22, sibling
documents via G23, Mermaid syntax via G21, the narrative label-discipline of X9
via G20, the human executive opening via G24, and diagram teaching-prose via G25.
Prose disciplines still require adversarial review: X1 mental-model quality, X3
explicit inversion, X4 voice, X8 prose-first teaching, X10 proof capability
completeness, X12 confidence honesty, X13 backward derivation quality, X14
anti-log causal structure, and X15 toil-removal judgment. The validator catches
structural shape; the adversarial gate catches the prose-discipline failures.
Both must run for `status: complete`.

**When drafting or reviewing any level and you need the full rationale, worked traps, or the exact prose-discipline wording for rules X1/X2/X3/X4/X6/X7/X8/X13/X14/X15, read `references/cross-level-rules.md`.** The validator-enforced rules (X5, X9, X10, X11, X12) keep their full bodies here because they bind a Phase gate. If `references/cross-level-rules.md` is unavailable, the one-line statements in the table below remain binding and the adversarial gate (Phase 5) catches prose-discipline violations.

| Rule | One-line normative statement | Enforcement |
|---|---|---|
| X1 | Every level leaves the reader a mental handle, not just a local table — pass the 4-test below. | parts machine-checked (G6/G11); prose via adversarial gate |
| X2 | Each level reuses ≥1 named entity from the prior level; no retroactive reveals (a name first used in L8 must have appeared in L1–L6). | machine-checked by validator G11 |
| X3 | When live evidence contradicts a prior claim, never silently correct — quote the original verbatim, show the live probe, name the inversion. | prose discipline |
| X4 | Engineer-to-engineer, first-person forensic ("I re-ran X — output was Y"); show the surprise where it occurred. | prose discipline |
| X5 | Every independently-inspectable source is a Markdown link or a written resolving access path (full body below). | validator G13 for final packages |
| X6 | Format follows information shape: code blocks only for code/commands/logs/output; timelines/pipelines/topologies are tables or Mermaid. | machine-checked via G14/G15/G16 |
| X7 | Topology diagrams pass the phone-screen test; split unreadable diagrams into table + smaller Mermaid. | prose discipline |
| X8 | Every dense table/diagram is wrapped in teaching prose — intro before (what it answers); after, prose that reads the mechanism, not a fact list. Diagrams teach the path. | prose discipline + G25 for diagrams |
| X9 | Evidence codes (A1/A2/A3, E-codes, reviewer names) NEVER appear in narrative prose — they live in the Evidence Ledger, table columns, and the Mutation log; the prose states status in human words (full body below). | machine-checked G20 |
| X10 | Build a Proof Capability Map before proof claims, pairing each claim family with its proof surface (full body below). | prose discipline + Phase-0 gate |
| X11 | Every Mermaid fence passes a parser/render check before delivery (full body below). | machine-checked by G21 |
| X12 | Confidence is computed from the Evidence Ledger only, with hard gates; assumptions never count as verified (full body below). | prose discipline + confidence gate |
| X13 | The Knowledge Contract drives backward derivation: each contract line maps to domain → primitive → visual (its ANGLE + cognitive job) → probe → challenge → section; beneath the matrix an "Angles excluded:" note names, per excluded angle, the incident fact that makes it empty. | machine-checked via G22 + G26 |
| X14 | Timeline supports causality; it never owns the document shape (a log-shaped RCA fails). | prose discipline |
| X15 | Toil removal is critical design, not automatic automation; every proposal is evidence-bound. | prose discipline |

The validator-gated rules X5, X9, X10, X11, and X12 keep their full bodies below because each binds a Phase gate; X1's 4-test is a quality gate kept compact here:

### Rule X1 — Mental-model 4-test (quality gate per level)

Every level must leave the reader a mental handle. The reader-facing mental-model map must pass: (1) **Plain-language takeaway** — a phrase the reader can say back without decoding internal skill jargon; (2) **First-principles pattern** — what remains true after incident-specific nouns are stripped away; (3) **Incident relevance** — why this pattern is needed to understand this RCA, not a generic lesson; (4) **Transfer value** — what this pattern would make the reader look for in a different incident. The artifact may use schema thinking internally; the RCA reader gets a mental-model map.

### Rule X5 — Clickable source contract (transfer rule, validator G13 for final packages)

Every source the reader can inspect independently is a Markdown link:

- repo, file, and line targets
- pull requests, commits, builds, pipeline runs, tickets, dashboards, wiki pages
- official docs and cloud portal resources

If a source cannot be linked because it lives behind a private CLI, expired
session, redacted export, or local-only path, write the resolving access path
next to the claim. Raw names such as "PR 172400", "pipeline 1413", or
"VPP - Infrastructure" are not enough in a final RCA when a link exists.

**Official-docs exploration (validator G26).** Beyond evidence links, the RCA
MUST embed at least one DIRECT official/vendor documentation URL for the
load-bearing external mechanism (the metric semantics, the SDK behavior, the
platform feature) in the reader-facing document, so the reader can go and
explore more with one click. A curated local evidence file (the
evidence-quarantine route) may SUPPLEMENT the direct URL — it never substitutes
for it. Topics with genuinely no public documentation declare it explicitly:
"No public official docs apply — <reason>". Silence is a validator FAILURE;
link RELEVANCE to the actual mechanism is judged at the Phase-5 adversarial
gate. Placement discipline holds: links live in ledgers, tables, and Go-deeper
surfaces; the narrative names the authority in words.

### Rule X9 — Evidence codes stay out of the narrative

Evidence codes (`A1`/`A2`/`A3`, `E8`-style probe IDs, internal reviewer names)
are audit metadata, NOT teaching prose. They NEVER appear bare in a narrative
sentence. They live in exactly these places: the **Evidence Ledger**, a dedicated
**evidence/Context table column**, the **Mutation log**, and fenced blocks. The
narrative carries the same epistemic status in human words — "the live Azure
metrics showed…", "this is an inference because…", "this remains unverified
because…". A reader must never have to learn the document's private code system
to follow the incident.

This is the inversion of the old "repeat the local decoder" rule. The fix for a
code in prose is not a nearby decoder; it is to move the code to the ledger and
restate the status in words. `scripts/validate-rca-completeness.sh` G20 fails any
narrative prose (outside tables, fenced blocks, and the ledger/Mutation-log
sections) that carries a bare `A1`/`A2`/`A3`, an `E`-code, or a reviewer name.
Claim classification is still mandatory (G7 / `check-claim-classification.sh`) —
it is satisfied by the human evidence phrasing in the prose OR by the code in the
adjacent Evidence Ledger row.

### Rule X10 — Proof Capability Map before proof claims

Before Phase 2 starts, create a **Proof Capability Map** that pairs each
load-bearing claim family with the proof surface needed to settle it:

| Claim family | Source of truth | Tool/API/MCP/CLI | Required context/access | Freshness probe | If blocked |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| repo state | remote-tracking branch or hosted repo API | `git`, `gh`, ADO API, repo MCP | repo path, remote, branch, auth | `git fetch --all --prune` or hosted API timestamp | A3 blocked + ask/escalate |
| runtime state | cloud/runtime control plane | `kubectl`, `az`, `oc`, cloud API, Rootly/MCP | subscription, cluster, namespace, tenant, RBAC | account/context probe before read | A3 blocked + named operator action |
| organizational memory | Obsidian/vault knowledge | `2ndbrain-obsidian` via CLI/MCP/filesystem ladder | valid vault path + relevant search terms | vault validation + bounded search | A3 blocked + exact missing vault/source |

The map is not an inventory of tools. It is the proof plan: if a row has no
tool, access context, freshness probe, or blocked escalation path, the RCA does
not yet know how it will prove the claim. A tool named without runnable access
(`kubectl` exists but no current context; `az` exists but wrong subscription;
MCP listed but disconnected) is not a capability.

### Rule X11 — Mermaid syntax is a proof surface

Mermaid is a reader-facing artifact. Every Mermaid fence in `output/rca.md` or
auxiliary diagrams must pass `scripts/check-mermaid-syntax.sh` or an equivalent
Mermaid parser/render check before delivery. If the parser/render path is
unavailable, do one of three things:

1. install/enable the parser/renderer and re-run the syntax check;
2. replace the diagram with a Markdown table plus prose carrying the same
   facts; or
3. keep the RCA at `status: review` and name the unchecked diagram as a
   blocked proof surface.

Do not rely on visual inspection of Mermaid source. Broken syntax is invisible
to a reader until rendering time, so source-only review is not evidence.

### Rule X12 — Confidence excludes assumptions

The RCA may include a confidence score only after the Evidence Ledger exists.
Calculate it from verified claim states:

```text
confidence = A1_confirmed / (A1_confirmed + A2_infer + A3_blocked + contradictions_open)
```

Then apply hard gates:

- Any A3 assumption that affects the root cause or fix path blocks
  `status: complete`; escalate it with the exact resolving probe or question.
- A2 claims may support explanation, but they do not count as verified evidence.
- Contradictions stay open until a probe resolves them; do not average them
  away.
- The confidence paragraph must name what would lower the score most quickly.

This is intentionally stricter than a feeling-based confidence statement. A
complete RCA has no uncleared assumption on the causal mechanism or fix plan.

(Full bodies of X13 backward derivation, X14 anti-log causal shape, and X15 toil-removal judgment are in `references/cross-level-rules.md`; their one-line binding statements are in the table above.)

## Lenses (views over the mental model, not separate disciplines)

When stuck on a mental-model map entry, switch lens — but the reader-facing
takeaway is the unit of work, not the lenses.

| Lens | Question to ask the mental-model entry |
|---|---|
| **Angles** | Have I seen the schema from structural / behavioral / failure-modal angles? |
| **Perspectives** | Does the schema hold from the on-call / operator / developer / adversary perspective? |
| **First principles** | What universal principle does the schema rest on? |
| **Systems** | Does the schema name interactions, boundaries, AND time — not just nodes? |

The lenses are *aids when stuck*, not coverage requirements. A mental-model
entry is good when it passes Rule X1; the lenses help you find a clearer
takeaway when the current wording is too internal or too table-like.

## The Holistic Ladder (the 12-level scaffold)

A reader with zero context becomes a master by accepting the RCA Knowledge
Contract first, then climbing twelve rungs in order. Each rung answers one
question and prepares the reader for the next.

```text
K0  RCA Knowledge Contract ........... "What must the reader be able to do?"
K1  Knowledge domain map ............. "Which domains/aspects structure this RCA?"
L1  Business / Functional ............ "Why does this system exist?"
L2  Repo system ...................... "Which code components are in play?"
L3  Runtime architecture ............. "Which deployed pieces touch this incident?"
L4  Application / SDK / data flow .... "What does the failing code actually do?"
L5  IaC / declarative contract ....... "What does the spec say should exist?"
L6  Pipeline / delivery .............. "How does spec become runtime (or fail to)?"
L7  Timeline ......................... "What happened, when?"
L8  Fix .............................. "What changes, what doesn't, why?"
L9  Verification ..................... "How do we know the fix works?"
L10 Lessons .......................... "What durable knowledge do I keep?"
L11 End-to-end command playbook ...... "Recreate this RCA from scratch."
L12 One-page on-call playbook ........ "Spot this class next time in 5 minutes."
S1  how-to-fix.md .................... "Repair safely and prove convergence."
S2  how-to-recreate-this-rca.md ...... "Let another human/agent replay it cold."
S3  sre-toil-removal-proposal.md ..... "Remove or automate recurring toil wisely."
```

**Selection rule**: scale levels to the incident. A 1-component bug needs L3-L9 only; a multi-repo cross-system incident (ours' canonical exemplar) uses all twelve. Do not invent levels that have no content; do not skip levels the incident actually exercises. See `references/holistic-ladder.md` for the per-level template + skip rules.

**Coherence rule**: each level's output must reuse the vocabulary the prior level introduced. If L4 names a component, L5 says how that component is provisioned by name. If L6 names a pipeline, L7 cites a real run by ID. Vocabulary breaks are the most common reason readers lose the thread.

## Context Reconstruction Doctrine

The RCA starts from ignorance. Do not assume the author knows the domain,
service, repos, topology, SDLC, or organization-local platform tools. Treat
"MFRR", "Ripple", "Feature Branch environment", "app-of-apps", "pipeline 1413",
or any local nickname as an unresolved term until a source explains it.

Before drafting L1 you **MUST** build a **Context Ledger** (in the RCA or `antecedents/context-ledger.md`); every unresolved dimension is `A3 UNVERIFIED[blocked]` with the exact resolving question. **When running Phase 0 context acquisition, read `references/context-reconstruction.md` for the Context Ledger column schema, the seven minimum context dimensions, and the mandatory 2ndbrain/Obsidian recall ladder (`$SECOND_BRAIN_PATH` → `$SECOND_BRAIN_VAULT_LOCAL` → validate `llm-wiki/_index.md` → search incident terms → copy as A2 INFER).** If that reference is unavailable, still build the ledger from repos/wikis/tickets and mark every unresolved dimension `A3 UNVERIFIED[blocked]`; do not silently proceed without it. A missing context ledger is not harmless — it forces the reader to supply the author's private knowledge.

## Platform-Mechanism Expansion

Organization-local platforms (Feature Branch/Ripple/app-of-apps/ephemeral envs) must be explained as mechanisms, not named as magic nouns (see H-READER-4). **When the incident touches such platform machinery, read `references/context-reconstruction.md` § Platform-mechanism expansion for the six construction questions and the environment-binding rule (independent vs shared runtime resources).** If unavailable, at minimum answer in L2/L6 prose: what it creates, what it glues, what data/control signal flows, and what ripples when an input changes.

## Inherited-Claim Staleness Pathology

Every claim arriving from outside this session — from a prior diagnosis doc, a slack message, a previous `git show origin/main:…` output, an old kubectl screenshot — is **INFER**, not FACT, until re-probed inside this session. The canonical failure mode of an authored RCA is a **stale-mirror INFER mislabeled FACT** (a `git show origin/main` read against a mirror not `git fetch`ed in days; a day-old kubectl status; a pipeline "skipped Apply" whose Timeline records were never read).

**Defense**: Phase 2 of this skill mandates a *freshness audit* of every inherited claim. **For the re-probe decision diagram and the git/kubectl/pipeline worked examples, read `references/claim-classification.md`.** Any inherited claim that cannot be re-probed in this session is downgraded to `[UNVERIFIED[blocked: <reason>]]` with the resolving probe named, never silently passed through as FACT. If that reference is unavailable, still treat every inherited claim as INFER until an in-session probe re-elevates it.

## Probe-Rationale Pairing

A command in an RCA is a *probe* — a question whose answer is one of the load-bearing claims. Every final command block must carry six things:

| Element | Why |
|---|---|
| The question being asked | So the reader knows what cognitive role the output plays |

