### Rule X12 — Confidence excludes assumptions

The RCA may include a confidence score only after the Evidence Ledger exists.
Calculate it from verified claim states:

```text
confidence = A1_confirmed / (A1_confirmed + A2_infer + A3_blocked + contradictions_open)
```

Then apply hard gates:

- Any A3 assumption that affects the root cause or fix path blocks
  `status: complete`; escalate it with the exact resolving probe or question.
- A2 claims may support explanation, but they do not count as verified evidence.
- Contradictions stay open until a probe resolves them; do not average them
  away.
- The confidence paragraph must name what would lower the score most quickly.

This is intentionally stricter than a feeling-based confidence statement. A
complete RCA has no uncleared assumption on the causal mechanism or fix plan.

(Full bodies of X13 backward derivation, X14 anti-log causal shape, and X15 toil-removal judgment are in `references/cross-level-rules.md`; their one-line binding statements are in the table above.)

## Lenses (views over the mental model, not separate disciplines)

When stuck on a mental-model map entry, switch lens — but the reader-facing
takeaway is the unit of work, not the lenses.

| Lens | Question to ask the mental-model entry |
|---|---|
| **Angles** | Have I seen the schema from structural / behavioral / failure-modal angles? |
| **Perspectives** | Does the schema hold from the on-call / operator / developer / adversary perspective? |
| **First principles** | What universal principle does the schema rest on? |
| **Systems** | Does the schema name interactions, boundaries, AND time — not just nodes? |

The lenses are *aids when stuck*, not coverage requirements. A mental-model
entry is good when it passes Rule X1; the lenses help you find a clearer
takeaway when the current wording is too internal or too table-like.

## The Holistic Ladder (the 12-level scaffold)

A reader with zero context becomes a master by accepting the RCA Knowledge
Contract first, then climbing twelve rungs in order. Each rung answers one
question and prepares the reader for the next.

```text
K0  RCA Knowledge Contract ........... "What must the reader be able to do?"
K1  Knowledge domain map ............. "Which domains/aspects structure this RCA?"
L1  Business / Functional ............ "Why does this system exist?"
L2  Repo system ...................... "Which code components are in play?"
L3  Runtime architecture ............. "Which deployed pieces touch this incident?"
L4  Application / SDK / data flow .... "What does the failing code actually do?"
L5  IaC / declarative contract ....... "What does the spec say should exist?"
L6  Pipeline / delivery .............. "How does spec become runtime (or fail to)?"
L7  Timeline ......................... "What happened, when?"
L8  Fix .............................. "What changes, what doesn't, why?"
L9  Verification ..................... "How do we know the fix works?"
L10 Lessons .......................... "What durable knowledge do I keep?"
L11 End-to-end command playbook ...... "Recreate this RCA from scratch."
L12 One-page on-call playbook ........ "Spot this class next time in 5 minutes."
S1  how-to-fix.md .................... "Repair safely and prove convergence."
S2  how-to-recreate-this-rca.md ...... "Let another human/agent replay it cold."
S3  sre-toil-removal-proposal.md ..... "Remove or automate recurring toil wisely."
```

**Selection rule**: scale levels to the incident. A 1-component bug needs L3-L9 only; a multi-repo cross-system incident (ours' canonical exemplar) uses all twelve. Do not invent levels that have no content; do not skip levels the incident actually exercises. See `references/holistic-ladder.md` for the per-level template + skip rules.

**Coherence rule**: each level's output must reuse the vocabulary the prior level introduced. If L4 names a component, L5 says how that component is provisioned by name. If L6 names a pipeline, L7 cites a real run by ID. Vocabulary breaks are the most common reason readers lose the thread.

## Context Reconstruction Doctrine

The RCA starts from ignorance. Do not assume the author knows the domain,
service, repos, topology, SDLC, or organization-local platform tools. Treat
"MFRR", "Ripple", "Feature Branch environment", "app-of-apps", "pipeline 1413",
or any local nickname as an unresolved term until a source explains it.

Before drafting L1 you **MUST** build a **Context Ledger** (in the RCA or `antecedents/context-ledger.md`); every unresolved dimension is `A3 UNVERIFIED[blocked]` with the exact resolving question. **When running Phase 0 context acquisition, read `references/context-reconstruction.md` for the Context Ledger column schema, the seven minimum context dimensions, and the mandatory 2ndbrain/Obsidian recall ladder (`$SECOND_BRAIN_PATH` → `$SECOND_BRAIN_VAULT_LOCAL` → validate `llm-wiki/_index.md` → search incident terms → copy as A2 INFER).** If that reference is unavailable, still build the ledger from repos/wikis/tickets and mark every unresolved dimension `A3 UNVERIFIED[blocked]`; do not silently proceed without it. A missing context ledger is not harmless — it forces the reader to supply the author's private knowledge.

## Platform-Mechanism Expansion

Organization-local platforms (Feature Branch/Ripple/app-of-apps/ephemeral envs) must be explained as mechanisms, not named as magic nouns (see H-READER-4). **When the incident touches such platform machinery, read `references/context-reconstruction.md` § Platform-mechanism expansion for the six construction questions and the environment-binding rule (independent vs shared runtime resources).** If unavailable, at minimum answer in L2/L6 prose: what it creates, what it glues, what data/control signal flows, and what ripples when an input changes.

## Inherited-Claim Staleness Pathology

Every claim arriving from outside this session — from a prior diagnosis doc, a slack message, a previous `git show origin/main:…` output, an old kubectl screenshot — is **INFER**, not FACT, until re-probed inside this session. The canonical failure mode of an authored RCA is a **stale-mirror INFER mislabeled FACT** (a `git show origin/main` read against a mirror not `git fetch`ed in days; a day-old kubectl status; a pipeline "skipped Apply" whose Timeline records were never read).

**Defense**: Phase 2 of this skill mandates a *freshness audit* of every inherited claim. **For the re-probe decision diagram and the git/kubectl/pipeline worked examples, read `references/claim-classification.md`.** Any inherited claim that cannot be re-probed in this session is downgraded to `[UNVERIFIED[blocked: <reason>]]` with the resolving probe named, never silently passed through as FACT. If that reference is unavailable, still treat every inherited claim as INFER until an in-session probe re-elevates it.

## Probe-Rationale Pairing

A command in an RCA is a *probe* — a question whose answer is one of the load-bearing claims. Every final command block must carry six things:

| Element | Why |
|---|---|
| The question being asked | So the reader knows what cognitive role the output plays |
| Why this command/API is authoritative | So the reader understands the source-of-truth choice |
| The selected fields / filters | So the reader can see what signal is extracted |
| The exact command | So the reader can re-run it byte-for-byte |
| The expected output (text-shape) + the decision rule | So the reader knows what answer to extract and what to do with it |
| The reusable principle | So the reader can choose the equivalent probe in a different stack |

**For the worked specimen of the six-part block (the az-eventhubs consumer-group probe, plus the branching-outcome and freshness-probe variations), read `references/probe-rationale-pattern.md`.** Without this pairing the RCA degrades into a bash-script dump the reader cannot map to the conclusions; with it, the reader replays every probe and learns the system *while* validating the conclusions. See `references/anti-patterns.md` for the failure modes (commands without rationale, expected-output-missing, decision-rule-implicit). If the reference is unavailable, the 6-element table above is the binding contract and `scripts/check-command-rationale.sh` still gates it.

## Decision Framework 1: Input mode

Decide once, at Phase 0, what you have:

```text
Input -> Mode -> What changes
existing diagnosis (verified or partial) -> ENRICH    -> Phase 2 freshness audit is heaviest
raw incident notes (slack/kubectl/az)    -> SYNTHESIZE -> Phase 0 inventory dominates; embed
                                                          freshness probes for any claim that
                                                          can't be re-verified now
live triage in progress                  -> ROUTE      -> Wrong skill — go to live triage,
                                                          come back when investigation is done
```

ENRICH and SYNTHESIZE share Phases 1–7; only Phase 0 weighting differs.

## Decision Framework 2: Level selection

For each of L1–L12, ask: "Does the reader's mastery require this level for THIS incident?"

| Level | Required if | Skip if |
|---|---|---|
| L1 Business | Reader is unfamiliar with the system's user-visible role | Reader is the team that owns it |
| L2 Repo system | Cross-repo incident OR reader is new to repos | Single-repo incident with known repo |
| L3 Runtime architecture | Cloud / K8s / multi-service deployment | Local dev, single binary |
| L4 SDK / code flow | Failure was in code or library, not config | Pure config error |
| L5 IaC | Resource provisioning is in scope | Not an IaC system |
| L6 Pipeline | Delivery / CI / approval gates were involved | Manual deploy or trivial CI |
| L7 Timeline | Multi-event incident OR multi-day latency | Single-event spot fix |
| L8 Fix | Fix is shipping with this RCA | Diagnosis-only mode (label the doc accordingly) |
| L9 Verification | Anything that would let a reviewer mistakenly accept a wrong fix | Truly trivial change |
| L10 Lessons | Account for durable learning. If no reusable lesson exists, state why in one sentence. | Do not force ritual lessons for tiny one-off fixes. |
| L11 Command playbook | Account for reproducibility. For command-heavy incidents, include full L11; for tiny/local incidents, a minimal replay proof or proof artifact may satisfy it. | Skip only by naming the proof surface that replaces it. |
| L12 On-call one-pager | Pattern is recurrent or worth promoting to a runbook | Truly one-off pathology |

If you are tempted to skip more than 3 levels, double-check Phase 1's endgame — the reader probably needs more, not less.

**Cargo-cult-depth guard**: if you chose all 12 levels but the incident class is a single-component bug or a single-binary local-dev failure, you are probably writing the wrong endgame's RCA. The golden mFRR example is large because it is multi-repo, multi-day, multi-system; copying that depth onto a 30-minute single-binary fix produces a doc no reader will finish. Length budget by reader-class: a next-shift on-call inheriting a multi-system context = 600–1200 lines; a developer hand-off on a single component = 150–400 lines. If your draft is far above its class budget, re-run Phase 1.

## Decision Framework 3: Adversarial dispatch points

Two mandatory dispatch points; one optional.

