605:    "summary": "An FBE 'feature-flag 401' is almost never the dev-mc shared App Config store. Each FBE slot reads its OWN per-slot Sandbox store vpp-appconfig-fbe-<slot>-<rand>.azconfig.io (RG rg-vpp-app-sb-401), and the VPP frontend init container injects that store's access-key CONNECTION STRING into a browser-served file (window.VUE_APP_AZ_CONFIG_CONNECTION_STRING in /etc/nginx/html/appconfig/appconfig.js). So the failing 'app configuration calls' are the BROWSER SPA calling .appconfig.featureflag%2F* directly over HMAC, visible in DevTools. 'I can see the FFs set properly in the app config' usually means looking at the WRONG store (the dev-mc vpp-applicationconfig-d from an earlier ticket). For Jupiter (Rec0BC1FTLV35) the store/key were healthy throughout; the 401 was a provisioning-window freshness condition (store created 09:29Z, flags 10:03Z, Duncan tested ~10:49Z against a 23-min-old frontend pod, healthy pod rebuilt 20:17Z) that self-resolved — Duncan confirmed 401->200.",
606:    "root_cause": "Per-slot FBE App Config store + browser-direct HMAC read of feature flags; transient credential/appconfig.js freshness during FBE provisioning. The dev-mc vpp-applicationconfig-d framing is a misdirection inherited from the earlier (by-design) VPN-network ticket.",
607:    "fix": "Probe the LIVE FBE, not dev-mc. kubectl ctx vpp-aks01-d (Sandbox): endpoint = `kubectl -n <slot> get secret application-secret -o jsonpath='{.data.connectionstrings_appconfig}' | base64 -d | grep -oiE 'Endpoint=[^;]+'`. Validate the key: `CS=...; az appconfig kv list --connection-string \"$CS\" --top 1` (200 = key valid -> not a key/RBAC problem). Have the user hard-refresh and capture the DevTools request (host=which store, Authorization Id=, status, Date). Provisioning-window 401s self-resolve on the frontend rebuild; do NOT touch dev-mc keys/RBAC/pipeline. Incidental: the connection string (Primary write key) is exposed to the browser - separate hardening follow-up.",
