13-summary: >-
14:  RESOLVED 2026-06-26 — Duncan confirmed the failing calls now return 200 (browser DevTools). CORRECTION
15-  (live-probe enrichment, task 2026-06-26-004): the Jupiter FBE reads its OWN per-slot Sandbox App Config
16:  store vpp-appconfig-fbe-jupiter-qvc.azconfig.io (RG rg-vpp-app-sb-401), NOT the shared dev-mc
17-  vpp-applicationconfig-d this document originally analyzed; the failing caller is the BROWSER SPA calling
18:  .appconfig.featureflag/* over HMAC (connection string injected into a browser-served appconfig.js). The
19:  store/key were healthy throughout; the 401 was a provisioning-window credential-freshness condition that
20:  self-resolved when the frontend pod rebuilt. The dev-mc hypothesis set (H0–H3) below targets the wrong
21:  store and is retained only as the original pre-probe reasoning trail. ORIGINAL SUMMARY FOLLOWS.
22:  Duncan Teegelaar (frontend engineer, returning to VPP) reports that his Jupiter FBE slot, viewed
23:  through AVD, gets HTTP 401 from Azure App Configuration (vpp-applicationconfig-d, dev-mc) so feature
24:  flags "cannot be set," even though he can see the flag values in the portal. A 401 on AVD is an
25-  AUTHENTICATION failure of the credential/token itself — categorically different from his EARLIER
26:  (2026-06-18, resolved) ticket where feature-flag fetch timed out on VPN because the store is
27:  private-endpoint-only ("everything through AVD"). Microsoft's data-plane contract is decisive: 401 =
28:  bad/expired/wrong-tenant token or a deleted/stale access key; a missing RBAC role is 403; a blocked
29:  source is 403/timeout. The diagnosis is a ranked HYPOTHESIS SET, not a verified single cause, because
30:  the one probe that collapses it — the exact failing call, its status and WWW-Authenticate body, plus
31:  the live disableLocalAuth/RBAC state — is AVD-gated and was not runnable from this analysis. Leading
32-  hypotheses (re-ranked after adversarial review) now LEAD with H0 — the FF-apply pipeline never
33:  applied/approved the flags (Duncan's own Sep-2025 precedent; predicts no real 401) — followed by the
34:  auth branches split by caller and WWW-Authenticate shape: H1 interactive token, H1-SP pipeline-SP
35:  token, H2 access-key read, H3 role gap (a 403, not 401). The reported "401" is a rusty filer's
36-  paraphrase and must be confirmed first. The how-to-fix is a safety-gated decision tree, not a blind fix.
