74-## Executive summary
75-
76:Duncan Teegelaar — a **frontend engineer** on the VPP / Flex Trade Optimizer team who, in his own
77-words, "[has] not worked on VPP in a bit" — opened a Platform intake ticket on 22 June 2026 saying that
78-his **Jupiter Flex Budget Engine (FBE)** slot, which he was inspecting **through AVD**, was getting
79:**HTTP 401** back from **Azure App Configuration** when feature flags were being set, even though he
80:could **see the flag values sitting correctly in the App Configuration store**. He noted it felt
81-"similar to my earlier one from Thursday about feature flags and FBEs."
82-
83:That earlier Thursday ticket is the trap this RCA exists to disarm. On 18 June Duncan reported that
84-feature-flag **fetch worked from AVD but not from the Eneco VPN**, and the platform team closed it
85:**by design**: the dev-mc App Configuration store is **private-endpoint-only**, so there is "no line of
86-sight outside the VNet" and AVD "is the way forward." That earlier symptom was a **connection timeout
87:on the network layer**. The new symptom is an **HTTP 401 from inside AVD** — i.e. the network path
88-already succeeded and the *credential* was rejected. **They are two different failures at two different
89-layers, and conflating them is the most likely way the next on-call gets this wrong.**
90-
91-The system works like this. VPP services have **two distinct ways of talking to App Configuration**.
92-The **read path** (a service loading its feature flags at runtime) connects with an **access-key
93-connection string** pulled from Key Vault. The **write / "set the flags" path** is an Azure DevOps
94-Terraform pipeline that authenticates with a **service principal's Microsoft Entra (Azure AD) token**
95-over the App Configuration **data plane**, and it needs the **App Configuration Data Owner** role on
96:the store. Crucially, *seeing the flags in the portal* uses a **third, separate permission** (the
97-Azure Resource Manager control plane) — so "I can see the flags" proves nothing about whether the
98-data-plane call that failed was allowed to authenticate.
99-
100:What does a 401 actually mean here? Microsoft's data-plane contract gives us a precise decision rule,
101:and that rule is the spine of this RCA — **but read one caveat first**: the "401" is Duncan's word in a
102-one-line intake ticket, *not* a captured HTTP status line, and he describes himself as rusty on VPP. So
103-the rule's job is to tell us *what to confirm*, not to license a conclusion before the status is
104:witnessed. The rule: on the App Configuration data plane, **401 = authentication failed** (no token, an
105-invalid / expired / wrong-audience / wrong-tenant Entra token, or a deleted / stale / mis-signed access
106:key), while **403 = authenticated-but-not-authorized**, which splits into a missing data-plane **role**
107:(403-RBAC) or a **blocked network source** (403 with a network `problem+json` body). A blocked VPN is a
108:403 or a timeout — *never* a 401. So **if** the failing call truly returns a literal 401 from inside AVD,
109-it points at the **credential/token itself**, not at networking and not (strictly) at a missing role —
110:and if the reported "401" is actually a 403 (or a paraphrase of a tooling banner), the cause shifts to a
111-role, the network, or the cases below. Confirming the literal status (L11 Step 2) is therefore the first
112-action, not an afterthought.
113-
114-Because the analysis could not run the one live probe that names the exact failing call, this RCA
115-delivers a **ranked hypothesis set**. Before ranking, resolve a question the word "set" hides: **which
116-caller is failing?** "The FFs cannot be set" can mean three different callers with three different
117:credentials — (i) Duncan running an interactive `az appconfig`/portal action from AVD (his own Entra
118-token), (ii) the **FF-apply ADO pipeline**, whose service principal `eneco-vpp-mc-dev` writes the flags
119:(the SP's Entra token — and "set" most literally denotes *this* path), or (iii) the **running FBE pod**
120-failing to *read* a flag (its access key). The status code alone does **not** tell you *whose*
121-credential failed, so the discriminator must capture both the status **and** which operation/caller
122-produced it.
123-
124-The hypotheses, re-ranked with that in mind:
125-
126-- **(H0) The flags were never applied — the FF-apply pipeline is pending its approval gate (or never ran
127-  for Jupiter).** This is the **strongest base-rate prior for this exact filer on this exact symptom**:
128:  Duncan hit precisely this on FBE *Kidu* in September 2025 ("FF didn't appear" → the App Configuration
129-  pipeline was waiting for approval; resolved on approval, no auth fix). A rusty engineer is *more*
130:  likely to forget the gate, and this predicts **no real 401 at all** — the "401" would be a frontend/SDK
131-  artifact of missing config. The RCA previously buried this as a "cheap exclusion"; it belongs in the
132-  ranked set.
133:- **(H1) An interactive AVD identity's token is stale or wrong-tenant** (a literal 401, `Bearer`).
134:  *Conditional on evidence that Duncan actually ran an interactive data-plane command* — which no
135-  evidence yet establishes, and which is an unusual action for a frontend consumer. Demoted from
136-  "leading" to "conditional."
137:- **(H1-SP) The FF-apply pipeline SP's token/secret is invalid or wrong-tenant** (a literal 401,
138-  `Bearer`, but a *different identity* — fixed by rotating the `eneco-vpp-mc-dev` service connection, not
139-  a personal re-login). This is the same-status, different-caller twin of H1 and is well-supported because
140-  the pipeline SP is the documented writer.
141:- **(H2) The access-key read path is broken** — keys disabled at the portal (deletes them → 401 for every
142:  connection-string caller) or a stale connection-string KV secret after rotation. This is the literal-401
143:  path **on the connection-string read** (note H1/H1-SP also produce literal 401s on the *token* path —
144:  the two are split by the `WWW-Authenticate` shape: `Bearer` vs HMAC, not by "literal vs not").
145-- **(H3) A data-plane role gap** — the calling identity lacks `App Configuration Data Owner`/`Reader`.
146:  Best fit for "set fails, values visible," but it surfaces as **403**, not 401 — so if the witnessed
147:  status is 403, H3 leads.
148-
149-The single probe that decides between all of them is: **capture the exact HTTP status, the
150:`WWW-Authenticate` / `problem+json` body, AND which caller produced the failing call.**
151-
152-Why this matters for the fix: each hypothesis implies a **different** repair, and several of the naive
153-fixes are **one-way doors**. Disabling/regenerating access keys deletes every existing key and breaks
154-every connection-string caller; "opening up networking" so VPN works violates the standing MC posture;
155-granting a frontend consumer **Data Owner** is an over-privilege. The how-to-fix is therefore a
156-**decision tree gated on that first probe**, not a single command. The durable lesson for the next
157:engineer: **401 ≠ 403 ≠ timeout; "I can see it in the portal" is control-plane, not data-plane; and on
158:Managed Cloud the answer is almost always "authenticate correctly from AVD," not "change the store."**
159-
160-## RCA Knowledge Contract
161-
162-After reading this RCA package, a zero-context reader can:
163-
164-1. **Draw** the two App Configuration access paths (key-based read, Entra-SP write) and the dev-mc
165-   private-endpoint boundary, and place the portal view as a third, separate plane.
166:2. **Trace** why an HTTP 401 observed from AVD is an authentication failure distinct from the earlier
167:   VPN timeout, using the 401/403/timeout decision rule.
168-3. **Reproduce** the discriminator investigation from cold (the AVD-gated probe sequence in L11),
169-   knowing what each probe proves.
170-4. **Reject** the three main false explanations: "it's the same as the VPN ticket," "it's a
171-   networking/whitelist problem," and "just grant Data Owner / disable local auth."
--
