337:## L4 — Application / data flow — How a 401 emerges while the portal still works
338-
339:**Anchor question: what exactly does the failing code/call do, and why 401 not 403?**
340-
341-There are two code paths into the data plane, and a third, unrelated path for the portal:
342-
343-- **Read path (runtime fetch).** The shared library calls `.Connect(connectionString)` — it presents an
344-  **access key**. `DefaultAzureCredential` is used here *only* to resolve Key Vault references that App
345:  Configuration hands back, **not** to authenticate to App Configuration. So a 401 on this path means
346-  the **access key is bad**: deleted (because someone disabled local auth) or stale (a rotated key whose
347-  new value never reached the connection-string secret).
348-- **Write / set-FF path.** The Azure DevOps Terraform pipeline writes `azurerm_app_configuration_feature`
349-  using the **pipeline service principal's Entra token** (`use_azuread_auth = true`) and therefore needs
350:  the **App Configuration Data Owner** role. A *missing role* here is a **403**; a *bad token*
351:  (expired, wrong tenant, wrong audience) is a **401**.
352-- **Portal view.** Seeing flag values in the portal uses **Azure Resource Manager (control-plane)**
353-  permission, which is *separate* from both data-plane modes. This is why "I can see the FFs set
354-  properly" is true at the same time the data-plane call fails.
355-
--
361-  E["Failing call"] --> C{Which caller?}
362-  C -->|"No error: flag just absent"| H0["H0: FF-apply pipeline not applied/approved"]
363-  C -->|"Interactive az/portal you"| Q1{"Status + body?"}
364-  C -->|"FF-apply pipeline SP"| Q1
365:  C -->|"Running FBE pod read"| Q1
366-  Q1 -->|"Timeout / no connect"| NET["NETWORK off-VNet/DNS = the earlier ticket"]
367:  Q1 -->|"403 + problem json ip/nsp-rejected"| NETB["NETWORK block 403: route/DNS, NOT a role"]
368:  Q1 -->|"403 no network body"| RBAC["RBAC: missing Data role (H3)"]
369:  Q1 -->|"401 Bearer, caller = you"| TOK["H1: interactive token stale/wrong-tenant"]
370:  Q1 -->|"401 Bearer, caller = pipeline SP"| TOKSP["H1-SP: rotate eneco-vpp-mc-dev SP secret"]
371:  Q1 -->|"401 HMAC Invalid Credential, FBE pod"| KEY["H2: access key deleted/stale"]
372:  Q1 -->|"Portal blade 401 in browser"| BROW["Portal/Edge PE quirk: use Chrome/Firefox"]
373-```
374-
375-How to read it: the fork has **two** axes — *which caller* and *which status+body*. Microsoft's contract
376:makes the statuses mutually exclusive (a 401 carries a `WWW-Authenticate` challenge — `Bearer` for a
377:token, HMAC for an access key; a network block is always a **403** with a `problem+json`
378:`ip-address-rejected`/`nsp-rejected` body; a missing role is a plain **403**). But the status alone does
379:**not** name *whose* credential failed: an interactive-you 401 and a pipeline-SP 401 both read
380:`401 Bearer`, yet one is fixed by your re-login and the other by rotating the SP's service-connection
381-secret. So capture **both** the status/body **and** the caller before acting.
382-
383-One sharp caveat the next engineer must not miss: the convenient probe
384-`az appconfig kv list --auth-mode login` exercises the **Entra-token arm only**. It can confirm an
385-interactive token (H1) and it returns 200 if *your* token is fine — but it **cannot reproduce the FBE
386:pod's access-key (HMAC) failure (H2)**, which lives on a different code path. A clean 200 from that probe
387:means "my Entra token works," not "the incident is resolved"; the FBE pod's own startup/SDK HTTP error is
388-the probe for H2.
389-
390-**Mental model to keep:** two axes select the branch — caller and status. A status read in isolation
391:("it's a 401") routes you to the wrong fix when the failing caller is the pipeline SP or the FBE pod, not
392-you.
