522-## L10 — Lessons — Durable knowledge
523-
524-**Anchor question: what should the next engineer keep, stripped of this incident's nouns?**
525-
526:1. **401 ≠ 403 ≠ timeout, and the difference routes the fix.** On the App Configuration data plane: 401 =
527:   the credential failed (bad/expired/wrong-tenant token, or deleted/stale access key); 403 = a missing
528-   role *or* a network block (the latter carries a `problem+json` body); timeout = off-VNet. Reading the
529-   exact status before acting eliminates whole cause families.
530-2. **Control-plane visibility is not (necessarily) data-plane authority.** "I can see it in the portal"
531-   does not prove the data-plane call authenticates — but be precise about why: the portal flag blade may
532-   itself read the *data* plane (so a working blade can be weak positive evidence of read auth, shifting
533:   suspicion to the *write*/pipeline path), the view may be cached/stale, and the blade can even 401 on a
534:   private-endpoint store in some browsers. So "I can see the flags" is a confusion to *rule out* — not
535-   the one thing that explains the ticket. Confirm on the failing operation, not the blade.
536-3. **"Similar to my earlier one" is a hypothesis, not a diagnosis.** Two tickets with the same words
537-   ("feature flags," "FBE") can be different layers; the timeline and the status code separate them.
538:4. **On Managed Cloud, the answer is usually "authenticate correctly from AVD," not "change the store."**
539-   Disabling keys, opening networking, or granting broad data roles are one-way doors / posture changes,
540-   not quick fixes.
541-5. **This is a member of the recurring credential/access class** (`LL-006`): per-incident fixes do not
542-   reduce recurrence; the class needs structural treatment (deterministic identities, documented "use
--
553-### Step 1 — Establish the AVD session context (freshness probe)
554-
555-- **Question:** am I authenticated to the right Managed Cloud dev tenant/subscription before I read
556-  anything?
557:- **Why this command/API:** App Configuration's data plane rejects a wrong-tenant token with a 401, so
558:  a stale `az` login can manufacture a false 401; establishing the session first makes every later probe
559-  test the *system*, not my session.
560-- **Fields selected:** signed-in user, tenant id, subscription id.
561-- **Expected output + decision rule:** `az account show` reports the dev-mc tenant and subscription
562-  `839af51e-…`; if it reports a different tenant/subscription, re-login before trusting any later probe.
--
568-az account show --query "{user:user.name, tenant:tenantId, sub:id}" -o json
569-```
570-
571-### Step 2 — Capture the exact failing call AND which caller (the master discriminator)
572:- **Question:** which caller failed (interactive *you* / the FF-apply *pipeline SP* / the *FBE pod*), and
573:  is the status a 401 (auth), a 403 (role/network), or a timeout (network)?
574:- **Why this is authoritative:** the HTTP status + `WWW-Authenticate`/`problem+json` body is the
575-  server's own verdict; the *caller* tells you *whose* credential it was — the same status from a
576-  different caller needs a different fix.
577:- **Fields selected:** the caller; HTTP status line; `WWW-Authenticate` shape (`Bearer` vs HMAC); any
578-  `problem+json` `type`.
579-- **Expected output + decision rule:** no error / flag absent → **H0** (pipeline not applied/approved);
580:  `401 Bearer` from *you* → **H1**; `401 Bearer` from the *pipeline run* → **H1-SP**; `401 HMAC
581:  "Invalid Credential"` from the *FBE pod* → **H2**; `403` no network body → **H3**; `403`
582-  `ip-address-rejected`/`nsp-rejected` → network; timeout → the earlier (closed) issue.
583-- **Principle:** read the source-of-truth error AND the caller before forming a hypothesis.
584-
585-```bash
586:# Ask Duncan WHICH caller failed (interactive command / FF-apply pipeline / FBE pod) — it selects the branch.
587-# (a) Entra-token arm — his interactive identity, or confirm your own token; grep for the verdict (do NOT blind-truncate):
588-az appconfig kv list --name vpp-applicationconfig-d --auth-mode login --top 1 --debug 2>&1 \
589:  | grep -iE 'HTTP/|www-authenticate|problem\+json|forbidden|unauthorized'
590-#   NOTE: --auth-mode login tests the ENTRA arm ONLY. A clean 200 here means YOUR token works;
591:#   it does NOT and cannot reproduce the FBE pod's access-key (HMAC) failure (H2).
592:# (b) Access-key (HMAC) arm — for H2, capture the FBE pod's OWN startup/SDK HTTP error:
593:#   kubectl -n <jupiter-ns> logs <fbe-pod> | grep -iE 'appconfig|401|invalid credential'
594-# (c) Pipeline-SP arm — for H1-SP, open the failing appconfiguration/devmc run and read its error.
